1. Ross Stores, Inc. replaced its $1.3 billion senior unsecured revolving credit facility (entered into February 2022) with a new facility, also for $1.3 billion, expiring in June 2030 with options to extend.
2. The new credit facility includes a $300 million sublimit for standby letters of credit and an option to increase the facility size by up to an additional $700 million.

3. The interest rates on borrowings under the new credit facility are variable, based on Term SOFR (or an alternate benchmark rate) plus a margin that depends on the Company’s long-term debt credit rating, and a commitment fee is payable quarterly.

1. TransDigm Group Inc. announced a definitive agreement on June 30, 2025, to acquire Simmonds Precision Products, Inc. for approximately $765 million in cash, including tax benefits.
2. Simmonds is projected to generate approximately $350 million in revenue for the calendar year ending December 31, 2025.
3. The acquisition is contingent upon regulatory approvals in the United States and standard closing conditions;  financing will be through existing cash on hand.
1. As of August 7, 2025, Robert Garechana will replace Alexander Brackenridge as Equity Residential's Chief Investment Officer, with Brackenridge retiring at the end of 2025.

2. Bret McLeod will join Equity Residential on July 22, 2025, as Executive Vice President – Finance, becoming Chief Financial Officer on August 7, 2025, with an annual base salary of $550,000, a target annual cash performance bonus of $687,500, and a target annual performance equity grant of $825,000.
3.  McLeod will receive a retention equity award valued at $1,250,000, vesting fully after three years of continuous employment, and will participate in the company's Executive Severance Plan.

1. On June 26, 2025, Williams Companies, Inc. priced a public offering of $1.5 billion aggregate principal amount of senior notes, comprised of $750 million in 4.625% senior notes due 2030 and $750 million in 5.300% senior notes due 2035.
2. The offering is expected to close on June 30, 2025, and Williams intends to use the net proceeds to repay near-term debt maturities and for general corporate purposes.

3.  The Underwriting Agreement lists Barclays Capital Inc., Citigroup Global Markets Inc., MUFG Securities Americas Inc., and Scotia Capital (USA) Inc. as joint book-running managers, along with several other passive book-running managers and co-managers.
1. Oracle anticipates exceeding $30 billion in annual revenue from a single cloud services agreement starting in fiscal year 2028.
2.  MultiCloud database revenue is growing at over 100%.
3.  Oracle's current fiscal year 2026 guidance remains unchanged despite the large new contract.
1. Carnival plc, a subsidiary of Carnival Corporation, commenced a €1.0 billion private offering of senior unsecured notes maturing in 2031 on June 30, 2025.
2.  The proceeds from this offering will fully repay Carnival Corporation's 2027 debt and partially repay its 2028 debt.
3. The new notes are expected to have investment-grade style covenants.
1. As of August 31, 2024, the company's 2024 Restructuring Plan, costing approximately $300 million pre-tax, was substantially complete.
2.  The company's effective income tax rate for the nine months ended May 31, 2025, was 28.5%, compared to 16.6% for the same period in 2024.
3.  On June 2, 2025, the company signed an agreement to acquire Rebound Technologies Group Holdings Limited, pending regulatory approval and customary closing conditions.

1.  Stanley Black & Decker appointed Christopher J. Nelson as President and Chief Executive Officer, effective October 1, 2025, and Donald Allan, Jr. as Executive Chairman of the Board, also effective October 1, 2025.
2.  Mr. Nelson's 2026 compensation includes a base salary of $1,300,000, a target annual bonus of 160% of his base salary, and annual equity awards with a target grant date value of $10,345,000.

3.  Mr. Allan will serve as Executive Chairman until his retirement on September 30, 2026, and will receive a 2026 base salary of $1,100,000, a target annual bonus of 150% of his base salary, and equity awards totaling $6,000,000.

1. Fortive Corp completed the spin-off of Ralliant Corporation (trading under "RAL" on the NYSE) on June 28, 2025, distributing one share of Ralliant common stock for every three shares of Fortive common stock held as of June 16, 2025.

2. Fortive estimates second-quarter 2025 revenue and core revenue as flat to slightly down, with Ralliant (formerly the Precision Technologies segment) declining mid-single digits as expected, due to increased pressure on tariff-related pricing and customer demand.
3.  Fortive intends to use the $1 billion in net cash proceeds from the Ralliant separation to repay outstanding debt and repurchase its common stock.
